# AgentLens

CLI tool that scans agent configuration across AI coding tools (Cursor, Claude Code, Codex, Copilot). Discovers skills, rules, commands, context files, hooks, and MCP server configs at both global and project level. With configured workspace roots, discovers and scans all projects across the workspace. Also provides a cost dashboard aggregating usage and costs from Claude Code and Cursor.

## Tech Stack

- TypeScript 5.9, ES modules (`"type": "module"`)
- Commander 14 for CLI
- Ink 6 + React 19 for interactive terminal UI
- gray-matter for frontmatter parsing (with manual fallback for YAML edge cases), smol-toml for TOML
- Chalk 5 for terminal styling
- sqlite3 CLI for reading Cursor's internal state database
- Build: `tsc` to `dist/`, dev: `tsx src/cli.ts`

## Project Structure

- `src/cli.ts` -- CLI entry, Commander commands: `scan` (default), `cost`, `where`, `troubleshoot`, `config`, `config tools`
- `src/scan.ts` -- Core scanning logic: `scanGlobal()`, `scanProject()`, `scanAll()`, `scanForWhereCommand()`. `scanDirectory()` supports multiple file patterns and recursive subdirectory traversal. `scanAll()` discovers and scans all projects from configured workspace roots.
- `src/parse.ts` -- File parsing: frontmatter, skills, MDC rules (with YAML error fallback), commands, MCP JSON/TOML, hooks from settings.json, Cursor user rules from state.vscdb via sqlite3 CLI
- `src/cost.ts` -- Cost aggregation: `fetchClaudeCodeCosts()` reads local JSONL usage logs and calculates per-model costs with static pricing; `fetchCursorCosts()` fetches usage from `GET cursor.com/api/usage` (premium requests, tokens) and plan info from `GET cursor.com/api/auth/stripe`; `fetchAllCosts()` orchestrates both
- `src/config.ts` -- AgentLens config at `~/.config/agentlens/config.json`, workspace root management, tool/category filter persistence (`disabledTools`, `disabledCategories`), `cursorSessionToken` for Cursor API auth, `LABEL_CATEGORIES` for label-based filtering, `discoverProjects()` recursively walks roots up to 3 levels deep looking for agent markers
- `src/render.ts` -- Static text output rendering (non-TTY), renders CURRENT, GLOBAL, PROJECT, and OTHER PROJECTS sections with tool/category filtering; `renderCostStatic()` for cost report output
- `src/troubleshoot.ts` -- Health check diagnostics
- `src/ai.ts` -- Claude Code CLI integration for AI analysis
- `src/symlink.ts` -- Symlink chain tracing
- `src/types.ts` -- Shared interfaces: `ScanResult`, `ProjectScan`, `ToolConfig`, `ConfigEntry`, `Diagnostic`, `TreeNode`, `McpServerEntry`, `AgentLensConfig`, `CostReport`, `ToolCostSummary`, `ModelCostBreakdown`
- `src/ui/` -- Ink components: `App.tsx` (page navigation between Scan/Cost, tree builder, CURRENT scope, multi-project support, lifted cursor/scroll/expandedOverride state, tool/category filtering), `TreeView.tsx` (vim navigation, focusNodeId, expand hints), `SearchBar.tsx`, `CommandBar.tsx` (`:` command palette for page switching with up/down selection), `DetailPanel.tsx` (linked entry navigation, linked vs cross-ref split, full description display), `CostView.tsx` (cost dashboard with scrollable report, usage bars, per-model breakdown), `HelpBar.tsx` (k9s-style keymap, view-adaptive for tree/detail/settings/cost), `SettingsView.tsx` (tool/category filter toggles), `theme.ts` (scope-colored headers)

## Key Patterns

- All imports use `.js` extension (Node16 module resolution)
- Scan locations are declarative arrays in `scanGlobal()` and `scanProject()` with a `type` field dispatching to the right parser
- Each scan category produces `ConfigEntry[]` wrapped in `ToolConfig`
- The `ConfigEntry` interface carries `name`, `path`, `exists`, optional `symlink`, `frontmatter`, and `description`
- Rendering (both static and interactive UI) is generic over `ToolConfig`/`ConfigEntry` -- new categories appear automatically
- Categories with entry names derived from data (not filenames): `MCP Servers` and `Hooks` use `e.name` directly for display
- `scanDirectory()` accepts `string | string[]` for file patterns and an optional `recursive` flag for walking subdirectories
- `ScanResult.projects` holds all discovered projects (excluding current) from configured workspace roots
- `discoverProjects()` skips `.`-prefixed, `node_modules`, and `vendor` directories; stops recursing once a project marker is found
- TUI uses two-level navigation: pages (Scan, Cost) switchable via `:` command bar, and views (tree, detail, settings) within the Scan page
- Cost data adapts display to available fields: Claude Code shows input/output/cache tokens with cost; Cursor shows tokens/requests with plan limit bar

## Adding a New Scan Category

1. Add a parser function in `parse.ts` returning `ConfigEntry[]`
2. Add location entries to the `locations` array in `scanGlobal()` and/or `projectLocations` in `scanProject()` with a new type
3. Add the type to the union and add a handler branch in the scan loop
4. If entries use `name` instead of filename for display, update the display name condition in `render.ts` and `ui/App.tsx`

## Adding a New Page

1. Add the page to `PAGES` in `src/ui/CommandBar.tsx` with `id`, `label`, and `desc`
2. Add the page type to the `page` state union in `src/ui/App.tsx`
3. Create a view component in `src/ui/` and render it conditionally based on `page` state
4. Add key bindings to `src/ui/HelpBar.tsx` (new `*Keys` array and condition)
5. Update `commandBarRows` in App.tsx if the page count changes

## Releasing

- Releases are automated via `googleapis/release-please-action@v4` in `.github/workflows/release.yml`
- On every push to `main`, release-please opens/updates a release PR that bumps `package.json` version and prepends to `CHANGELOG.md` based on conventional commits (`feat:`, `fix:`, `chore:`, etc.)
- Merging the release PR creates a GitHub release + tag, which triggers npm publish and Homebrew tap update
- Config files: `release-please-config.json` (package settings), `.release-please-manifest.json` (current version)

## Conventions

- No emoji in code
- Minimal comments -- only for non-obvious logic
- Error handling: silent catch with empty return (scanning is best-effort)
- Paths displayed with `~` prefix via `tildify()` helper
- Always run `npm run build` after any code change (binary at `./dist/cli.js` runs compiled output)
